Description: 
Art historian Janina Ramirez investigates what illuminated 
manuscripts commissioned for the kings of England 
between the ninth and 16th centuries reveal about the 
evolution of the country's art, culture and monarchy. 
She begins by exploring the British Library's collection of 
royal manuscripts, encountering books that are more than 
1,000 years old and learning about the first Anglo-Saxon
 rulers to create a united England. She also discovers 
how animal skins are transformed into vellum, the material 
on which the texts were written.
